%I A396469 #52 Jun 28 2026 10:38:34
%S A396469 2,3,23,37,47,61,223,233,743,1237,11813,39209,518057,3131537,7810427,
%T A396469 40481087,99241183,637496077,1520343073,10683103157,22935190549
%N A396469 Primes not representable as sums of the form q_1^{k_1} + ... + q_r^{k_r}, where q_1,...,q_r are distinct earlier terms of this sequence and k_i >= 1.
%C A396469 Open problems:
%C A396469  (1) What is the asymptotic growth of this sequence?
%C A396469  (2) Is there any efficient way to calculate the sequence?
%C A396469 The sequence is infinite. See Hartley (2026).
%H A396469 Nakul Badjatya, <a href="https://gist.github.com/sunitabadjatya6-cmyk/33d04ff3224a5c54504d387d7d7d7904">SageMath program</a>
%H A396469 Michael Hartley, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/q/5139839">Proof that the sequence is infinite</a>, Mathematics Stack Exchange, 2026.
%e A396469 Start with first prime 2. Now as the sequence is empty, 2 is admitted to the sequence.
%e A396469 Now to check whether 3 belongs to the sequence, we have to check if one can have 2^k = 3 with k >= 1. Since this is not possible, 3 is admitted.
%e A396469 The next prime is 5. But 2^1 + 3^1 = 5, so 5 is not admitted to the sequence.
%o A396469 (SageMath) # See Badjatya link
